# API Route Conventions

## Response Shape

All API routes return consistent JSON:

```typescript
// Success
{ "data": { ... } }

// Error
{ "error": { "code": "ENTITY_NOT_FOUND", "message": "Entity with ID xyz not found." } }
```

Never return bare values or arrays at the top level.

## Input Validation

- Validate all inputs (body, query params, route params) with Zod at the top of the handler.
- Return 400 with the validation error details on failure.

## HTTP Status Codes

- 200: success with body
- 201: resource created
- 204: success, no body
- 400: invalid input
- 401: missing or invalid authentication
- 403: authenticated but not authorized
- 404: resource not found
- 409: conflict (duplicate entity name, etc.)
- 429: rate limited
- 500: unexpected server error (log the full error, return generic message)

## Route Handler Structure

```typescript
export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  // 1. Parse and validate input
  // 2. Authenticate (check session/token)
  // 3. Authorize (check ownership/permissions)
  // 4. Delegate to service function in lib/
  // 5. Return structured response
}
```

## Business Logic

- Route handlers are thin. All business logic lives in `src/lib/` service modules.
- Route handlers handle HTTP concerns only: parsing, auth checks, status codes, response formatting.

## Auth

- Owner-authenticated routes: verify NextAuth session via `auth()`.
- Public AIA endpoints (`/oauth/token`, `/.well-known/*`, `/status`): no session required.
- Entity management routes (`/v1/entities/*`): require owner session + ownership check.
